Thought this might be an interesting line of discussion, in light of some of the comments in &quot;Vietnam - myths and reality&quot;.  How did &quot;the media&quot; portray 'Nam?  What sort of portrayal do us vets want?<br><br>
To start off, let me justify my choice of `Apocalypse Now' as a good movie.  Most vets really dislike that film; I'm a vet who thinks it's one of the best to come out of the 'Nam era.  Why?  It certainly isn't &quot;reality&quot;, so if you're looking for a realistic picture of the war, watch something else (what, I don't know - maybe `Hamburger Hill', but even that would only match a certain sort of reality).  The reason I think this is a good movie is that it uses 'Nam as a vehicle to examine what could happen when someone pursuses &quot;good&quot; ends to their logical conclusion, when one has the power to do almost anything.  Most of you probably know that the movie is actually based on Joseph Conrad's &quot;Heart of Darkness&quot;.  Read the book, read Michael Herr's &quot;Dispatches&quot; (Herr was a consultant on the movie and the scene at the bridge near Cambodia was based on Herr's experience at Khe Sanh) then watch the movie.  It will change your perspective on this one from &quot;pretty weird&quot; to &quot;right on&quot; - or, if it doesn't you'll at least see what Francis Ford was after.
